observations.recommendation:
In relation to the above observations, we recommended that the LCE:
(1) update the Inventory and Disposal Committee thru an issuance of a new Executive Order;
(2) require the:
(a) Property Officer in coordination with the Inventory Committee to perform its mandated function of conducting the physical count of the assets of the LGU and to render the corresponding report;
(b) Municipal Accountant and Property Officer, to:
(i) exert more efforts in locating documents pertinent to the acquisition of its PPEs and consider the option for a one-time cleansing of the PPE accounts provided COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020;
(ii) maintain their respective PPE records; and
(iii) reconcile their records at least on a quarterly basis; and
(3) Disposal Committee to facilitate the disposal of unserviceable PPE in accordance with the prescribed guidelines and procedures.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
(a) instruct the:
(i) Acting Municipal Accountant and MSWDO to submit the required documents which the Audit Team requested in order to render complete audit conclusion;
(ii) Acting MSWDO to be prudent and diligent in performing her functions and ensure that standards and parameters set by the authoritative bodies related to MSWDO’s mandate are fully and satisfactorily observed and complied with;
(b) revisit the guidelines on the qualifications on the assessment of the applicants of the Housing Program and/or institute appropriate remedies for the delinquent debtor; and
(c) formulate policy on the grant of AICS and other Financial Assistances that would define or designate, among others the: (i) qualifications/eligibilities of the beneficiaries; (ii) commensurate amount of grant for designated condition and/or situation; (iii) procedures to be employed on screening and selection; and (iv) constitution of grievance mechanism and monitoring.

We recommended that the Management:
(a) exert best efforts in implementing its COVID-19 Vaccination Program in view of the Philippine National Deployment and Vaccination Plan for COVID-19 Vaccines guidelines;
(b) intensify the information campaign to the public to spread awareness of COVID-19 vaccine benefits.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive (LCE) agreed to direct:

the Municipal Social Welfare Officer (MSWO) and/or the designated MSWDO to be more diligent in the preparation of payrolls and distribution of financial assistance of same nature in the future base on the DSWD approved list of qualified beneficiaries to avoid incurrence of similar lapses;

the Municipal Treasurer and the OIC Municipal Accountant, in the implementation of similar forthcoming projects, to-

closely coordinate with the MSWDO in facilitating the review of payroll base on approved DSWD and/or other funding agencies list of beneficiaries to prevent the inclusion of unqualified recipients in the payroll; 

consistently observe, monitor compliance on timely submission of liquidation reports and refund, if any, of unutilized fund to the source agency; and 

ensure that no redistribution of returned fund will be effected unless prior approval from the funding agency is secured to guarantee that the limited government resources will be hand over to the intended and qualified beneficiaries of the program.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct:

a.	the OIC Municipal Accountant to –

strictly observe the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002 on the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances;

issue the necessary demand letters to the accountable officers/persons, requiring them to settle their respective outstanding cash advances;

avoid the recurrence of similar lapses, endeavor to strengthen the internal control system for cash advances which would assure that cash advances are liquidated or reported on as soon as the purpose of the same is served, in compliance with Section 89 of PD No. 1445 and COA Circular 97-002;

exhaust all remedies/actions for the recovery and/or enforcement of liquidation of the subject long overdue outstanding cash advances; and 

file a request for authority to write off all dormant unliquidated cash advances to the COA Audit Team Leader and/or Supervising Auditor pursuant to COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016, if warranted.

b.	the Municipal Treasurer to strictly observe the timely liquidation of cash advances for payroll within the prescribed period to prevent the accumulation of unliquidated cash advances at any given period and ensure that all cash advances are fully liquidated at year-end.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct:

a.	the Municipal Assessor to exert extra effort in securing all documents needed for the titling of the subject lots being occupied by the Municipal Government and to coordinate with the concerned Offices, such as the DENR, Registry of Deeds, Bureau of Internal Revenue, etc. to facilitate the completion of titling processes; 

b.	the Municipal Budget Officer, in coordination with the Municipal Assessor and the Municipal Treasurer, to 

prepare an estimate of expenses to be incurred in the titling of subject lots and include the same in the budget preparation and; 

seek appropriate and possible legal remedies to recover the property from alleged claimant, to ensure right of ownership over the subject real properties.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive 

(a) require the Treasurer’s Office to submit to the Accountant the Certified List of Real Property Tax Delinquency (Basic and SEF) as of December 31, 2019; 


(b) instruct the Accounting Office to (i) maintain subsidiary ledger or schedules of RPT/SET Receivables showing the name of delinquent taxpayers, the amount due and collectible to support the receivable account balances; and (ii) regularly reconcile the said balances with the Certified List of Real Property Tax Delinquency prepared by the Municipal Treasurer to ensure fair presentation of balances in the Financial Statements.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to direct the Municipal Administrator, the designated Business Permit and License (BPL) Officer, and the Municipal Treasurer to 
(a) strictly comply with the provisions of the Municipal Revenue Code covered by SB Resolution No. 26 S-2017 in the assessment and collection of business taxes; 
(b) apply all alternative procedures and efforts to be able to establish the correct amount of gross sales/receipts of every business establishment in the locality; 
(c) refrain from assessing business tax dues based on verbally declared gross sales/receipts;       
(d) require business establishment to submit the original copies of Sworn Statement of Gross Sales/Receipts and the true photocopy of Income Tax Returns to check the correctness of paid business taxes; and 
(e) cause the collection of the total amount of ₱502,172.50 corresponding to business tax deficiencies in CY 2017.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to direct the Municipal Administrator, the designated Business Permit and License (BPL) Officer, and the Municipal Treasurer to:
(a) strictly comply with the provisions of the Municipal Revenue Code covered by SB Resolution No. 26 S-2017 in the assessment and collection of business taxes;
(b) apply all alternative procedures and efforts to be able to establish the correct amount of gross sales/receipts of every business establishment in the locality;
(c) refrain from assessing business tax dues based on verbally declared gross sales/receipts;
(d) require business establishment to submit the original copies of Sworn Statement of Gross Sales/Receipts and the true photocopy Income Tax Returns to check the correctness of paid business taxes; and
(e) cause the collection of the total amount of ₱502,172.50 corresponding to business tax deficiencies in CY 2017.
